<subSubSection id="C9446DFBFE1D3C5CE49A2C8C970236E9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3ABF12D5BAF74A36F324DE17027223C5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A36F69C1057139A908EA53C26F5221CF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A rare plant of Brazil and Bolivia. In Bolivia it is characteristic of very dry forest between 1400 and 2000 m on the slopes of the 
<normalizedToken id="7ACD7DBB03B0C7454573CA7A168884BA" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Grande valley and its tributaries. Although large and conspicuous, there are few collections and it is clearly rare with a very restricted distribution. The only confirmed record from Brazil is the type collection.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B19F3DB6017771E7B02AF67F0ABD017" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="D7390DE80D4A6DE566DC07DE6B87C979" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BRAZIL. Minas Gerais</emphasis>
: Type of 
<taxonomicName id="9A40504C32FCAFCC65D93B7E587C27BD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="calyptrata">
<emphasis id="003E9B295D3929E8E2B86504F0E7AC8C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea calyptrata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="18FBA370CF97106D6174BD2EC8E8A37F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="406E1A4D064A9D946A88660085F3429F" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">BOLIVIA. Chuquisaca</emphasis>
: Boeto, below Nuevo Mundo, 
<emphasis id="B1471F803386588F5629E8E8B819DC9E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
20496 (BOLV, HSB, K, LPB); 
<emphasis id="25E62B05C314BCB3F4F331D101E37BF9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood et al.</emphasis>
27659 (OXF, K, LPB, USZ). 
<emphasis id="32A9C16F7BBFA9E6E98D9CB1614688F9" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Santa Cruz</emphasis>
: Saipina, 
<emphasis id="FBBC7F5A3B1F0B1802207D137883C434" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J. Balcazar 354</emphasis>
(OXF, LPB, MO, USZ); Alto Mairana, 
<emphasis id="66DD8533BB37C5AD0EAA58CC841CA59B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. Nee</emphasis>
49257 (NY, USZ); between Pucara and Santa Rosita, 
<emphasis id="CCAC8E9E86AEB11D886D35637424605D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">J.R.I. Wood &amp; M. Mendoza</emphasis>
21472 (K, LPB, USZ).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="38804B305D8E4A27DE1305EF509FC443" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="78E4E050D1CC11605F3F7D67A9B1F544" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E29D66DD00D08FB91A847B355CB7A71" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species because of its liana habit, persistent bracteoles appressed to the calyx, large tomentellous sepals and pink flowers. The whole plant is subtomentose with whitish hairs. The very long sepals (14-22 mm in length) serve to distinguish it from other somewhat similar species, such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C548E8507BF1628789DA0297AD95DA4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis id="07B715E31E6B920B30FAF1F129207586" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC000230982CFDA33A0D98B6A30DECB1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis id="1A4F346912A0829B2939C952C736F063" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A.L. Brochado</emphasis>
154 (IBGE, OXF) from P.N. Das Emas, 
<normalizedToken id="68C7B8FDF7C48961227091C32D05C064" originalValue="Goiás">Goias</normalizedToken>
may constitute the first modern collection from Brazil. However, although the inflorescence is similar, the leaves lack the characteristic reticulate venation on the underside.
</paragraph>
